column1: vP_VihdeIGY|The New York Times|"We're Taught Education Can End Poverty. Here's the Truth. | NYT Opinion"|"Text by Nicholas Kristof
Around the world we talk a good game about the importance of education
column2: but we rarely act as if we mean it.

column1: Here’s an unlikely exception: Sierra Leone
column2: one of the world’s most impoverished countries. In the video above
column3: I travel to Sierra Leone to chronicle that country’s campaign to get all children in school — and then to get them to actually learn to read
column4: even in ramshackle schools with no electricity or plumbing.

column1: The children broke my heart and also inspired me. If Sierra Leone can do this
column2: other countries can — and surely the United States can emulate that same determination to help every child learn.

column1: This education revolution in Sierra Leone is the brainchild of President Julius Maada Bio and his youthful minister of education
column3: Sengeh was working for IBM when President Bio asked him to come home and help his country — but now they face a test. Nationwide elections will be held late this month
column4: with Bio campaigning for another term.

column1: I wrote a column (https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/24/opinion/education-revolution-sierra-leone.html)  about what we can learn from Sierra Leone — and about the ways the revolution still falls short: Children are sometime beaten for failing to pay school fees that are in fact illegal. Despite these failings
column2: what I take away most is the hope reverberating through the nation. The world
column4: has much to learn from this nation’s determination to give every child an education. See it for yourself in this short film.

column1: XlnspY2wOVw|CNBC|"Why The Education System Is Failing America | CNBC Marathon"|"CNBC Marathon explores if why the education system in the U.S. is struggling by taking a hard look at the Common Core

column2: Common Core was an ambitious initiative to revolutionize the American education system. National leaders from Bill Gates to President Obama supported the idea and it cost an estimated $15.8 billion to implement. Years later
column3: research showed the new curriculum had minimal impact on student performance. So why did Common Core fail? Can a common curriculum be successful for all students?

column2: teachers earn nearly 20% less than other professionals with similar education and experience
column3: according to the Economic Policy Institute. In many states
column4: their wages are below the living wage
column5: forcing teachers to seek secondary jobs to supplement their income or leave the profession all together. So why are teachers paid so little and how can the U.S. fix that?

column1: And the majority of U.S. students report they've had sex before graduation
column2: which means the type of sex education they receive can be a big deal
column3: for themselves personally and for the economy. The federal government doesn't have any official regulations for what schools must include in sex education curriculum
column4: which has lead to inconsistent lessons across the country. Watch the video above to learn why sex education is so crucial for the economy and what happens when some students are left behind.

column1: ovxXYMsz37g|VICE News|"The Price of Education In China | Gen 跟 China"|"In July 2021
column2: the Chinese Communist Party announced new regulations that they said would reduce pressure on parents and children
column3: known as the double reduction policy. The new law banned private education companies from offering after-school tutoring in core school subjects. Chinese students and parents view good academic performance as a way to climb the country’s social ladder
column4: with a child’s studies often being prioritised above all else and exam pressure taking a toll on mental health. The new policy brought to heel China’s ballooning USD 120 billion private tutoring sector
column5: but the policy change has led to a tutoring black market
column6: which could benefit the wealthy and price out poorer families.

Why does our Foot Fall Asleep?
Many people believe that when our foot falls asleep
column2: basically the blood supply has been cut to our foot.

column1: But the real answer is that it has to do more with our nerves as compared to our blood. Nerves are like cables which run through our entire body.
Their main function is to carry electrical impulses or messages between our brain and our body.

column2: when we sit on our foot
column3: the nerves in that area are temporarily compressed.

column2: these nerves are not able to send any message to our brain or receive any message from our brain. As a result
column3: the connection between our brain and our foot is cut off.

column2: it feels like our foot has fallen asleep.

column1: Daily Planet reporter Lois Lane receives an assignment to investigate the discovery of a Kryptonian scout ship in the Canadian Arctic. Clark enters the ship disguised as a worker and learns from its artificial intelligence (AI)
